WEBVTT

00:00.098 --> 00:03.003
Well, good morning, Menlo Church, and welcome back.

00:03.143 --> 00:08.392
Today, we are finishing our series called Perfect, talking about kids.

00:08.692 --> 00:15.404
And if you've ever spent any time with a toddler, maybe you have one, you have experienced something that I call kid logic.

00:15.444 --> 00:16.145
I have four kids.

00:16.165 --> 00:17.868
I've experienced kid logic for a long time.

00:18.308 --> 00:21.714
And it's the ability to be 100% confident

00:21.826 --> 00:28.499
and 100% wrong at the same time, and you're like, I thought this was about kids, not a marriage sermon, Phil, that's weird.

00:29.220 --> 00:31.965
My favorite example, that one took a minute.

00:32.226 --> 00:34.670
I like heard a couple of you getting, you laugh, it's okay.

00:35.271 --> 00:43.026
My favorite example of this is kind of the ostrich strategy that we see with really little kids that are still learning object permanence.

00:43.106 --> 00:48.112
And when they're playing peekaboo with you, they kind of, you know, they put their hands over their face and they say peekaboo.

00:48.132 --> 00:53.358
And in that moment, in their mind, they've been teleported to a different place and you have ceased to exist.

00:53.398 --> 00:58.144
The moment they pull their hands away, they've teleported back and they look at you and I get it.

00:58.244 --> 01:00.046
Like the logic is airtight.

01:00.106 --> 01:03.310
If I can't see you, you can't see me.

01:03.430 --> 01:09.778
And they believe that their lack of vision means that you are invisible, that you literally disappear.

01:10.178 --> 01:20.957
Now, we laugh at little moments like this with kids because they're cute and sweet and fun, but I honestly think that a lot of us live our spiritual lives with a similar kind of logic.

01:20.977 --> 01:30.253
We think that if we ignore God that he won't see us, that he won't bother us, that he won't interfere, we think that if we hide our sin, if we hide our shame, if we hide our failures, that God won't know about them.

01:30.614 --> 01:35.282
But just like with a child, we don't see the whole picture.

01:35.458 --> 01:37.200
Now don't get me wrong, we do see a lot.

01:37.280 --> 01:39.303
Actually, that's kind of part of the problem.

01:39.343 --> 01:43.107
We basically live in a moment with unlimited information.

01:43.888 --> 01:49.295
If you aren't careful, like we're in a spot right now where we can assume we're actually all knowing.

01:49.335 --> 01:52.819
If you remember, that was kind of the first temptation of mankind.

01:53.360 --> 02:00.088
We think we're like God because we actually have the whole world in our pocket or in our hand at any given time.

02:00.588 --> 02:05.394
But God has something that we don't, which is unlimited wisdom too.

02:05.954 --> 02:10.938
And so before we dive into the message this week, talking about kids, I want to pray for us.

02:10.998 --> 02:22.809
And I know that God's been working on us as individuals, families, marriages, parents over these last few weeks at all of our campuses in San Mateo, Mountain View, Saratoga, Menlo Park, people joining us online.

02:23.069 --> 02:35.239
And then on top of that, you're scrolling through and watching tragedies take place around the world and in cities across the country and people with very different policy positions and very different politics.

02:35.279 --> 02:35.940
I think all

02:35.920 --> 02:37.622
are screaming out.

02:37.682 --> 02:40.546
Can we just see justice come forward?

02:40.566 --> 02:42.829
Can we just see the violence end?

02:43.670 --> 02:46.774
And so wherever you are, however you're joining us today, I'm gonna pray for us.

02:47.435 --> 02:53.764
And I'm gonna ask that God would meet us right here, that God would show up through His people to bring hope into a world that needs it.

02:53.904 --> 02:54.605
Would you pray with me?

02:55.967 --> 02:56.848
God, thank you so much.

02:57.689 --> 03:00.733
Thank you that prayer for us is not a last resort.

03:00.853 --> 03:02.896
It is not a flippant excuse to do nothing.

03:03.256 --> 03:04.658
It is the first place we go.

03:05.122 --> 03:10.568
It is the opportunity to not only change our hearts and change our perspective, but to change a broken and dying world.

03:11.469 --> 03:14.213
And so we pray for marriages to be restored.

03:14.253 --> 03:17.196
We pray for families to be put back together, God.

03:17.216 --> 03:21.561
We feel the way and the challenge, even in the message we're about to bring.

03:21.581 --> 03:28.449
And we pray for a world, a world where violence, God, we pray that peace would reign and rule, that your kingdom would come in Minneapolis.

03:28.469 --> 03:31.793
Your kingdom would come in Iran as it is in heaven.

03:31.873 --> 03:32.594
We pray that

03:32.706 --> 03:37.252
the hope of heaven would invade the hurts of this world in a way that is unmistakably you.

03:38.034 --> 03:38.835
Would you help that be true?

03:38.875 --> 03:41.819
Not just out there, but in here right now with me too, in Jesus' name.

03:42.640 --> 03:42.921
Amen.

03:44.463 --> 03:47.307
We live in a pretty unique moment in history.

03:47.647 --> 03:50.111
Information is basically everywhere.

03:50.151 --> 03:51.713
It can feel kind of unlimited.

03:52.254 --> 03:56.079
You probably have a phone in your pocket right now, right?

03:56.720 --> 04:00.786
And right now we find ourselves kind of drowning in data.

04:01.058 --> 04:08.132
But while information is everywhere, knowledge, what is actually truthful information, it requires curation.

04:08.172 --> 04:09.675
You can't just take information.

04:09.695 --> 04:11.399
You have to narrow it down.

04:11.439 --> 04:15.186
You have to sift through the noise to find what's actually true.

04:15.522 --> 04:25.157
The Apostle Paul wrote to a young student, a young mentee and protege in the first century named Timothy, and he flagged the same concern even back then when he said this.

04:25.197 --> 04:30.025
He said, have nothing to do with irreverent, silly myths.

04:30.085 --> 04:32.809
And you're like, I didn't think they had social media back then.

04:33.170 --> 04:35.794
Rather, train yourself for godliness.

04:36.066 --> 04:47.457
For while bodily training is of some value, godliness is of value in every way as it holds promise for the present life and also the life to come.

04:48.418 --> 04:56.806
And honestly, like if we just use that as a mirror right now, we are not doing a great job of sifting through what's true and what's a lie.

04:57.607 --> 05:03.052
We laugh at how young kids process and think and we think that's a cute game or that's a cute idea that you think it works that way.

05:03.112 --> 05:05.394
Kids are so gullible, that's adorable.

05:05.602 --> 05:08.085
But look at us, right?

05:08.105 --> 05:11.149
We live in an era of hyperspeed gullibility.

05:11.910 --> 05:18.959
We see a headline that confirms what we already want to believe, usually something that makes us angry at those people.

05:19.340 --> 05:20.842
And we believe it instantly.

05:20.862 --> 05:21.823
We don't check the source.

05:21.883 --> 05:23.025
We don't look for context.

05:23.045 --> 05:24.206
We don't ask if it's true.

05:24.527 --> 05:26.750
We just ask if it makes us feel righteous.

05:26.890 --> 05:31.436
And honestly, if it makes us feel mad, we hit share and we click forward.

05:31.456 --> 05:33.298
I've had some folks do that to me this week.

05:33.762 --> 05:36.425
We have confused outrage with insight.

05:36.826 --> 05:40.610
We think, like, I'm angry, therefore I must be right.

05:40.670 --> 05:41.812
And that isn't wisdom.

05:42.472 --> 05:43.674
That's just childish.

05:43.714 --> 05:45.135
And it's childish at any age.

05:45.616 --> 05:50.762
That's kid logic with AI and a smartphone, and we should know better.

05:51.583 --> 05:58.571
See, we think that we are doing our research when in reality we are just letting an algorithm feed us comfort food for our biases.

05:59.332 --> 06:00.754
And here's the hardest part.

06:01.506 --> 06:03.869
Wisdom has never been more scarce.

06:05.070 --> 06:07.993
Why is wisdom so rare in the information age?

06:08.013 --> 06:09.255
Well, it's because you can't download it.

06:09.295 --> 06:10.796
It's not transactional.

06:10.876 --> 06:13.519
It's not immediately available through a device in your hand.

06:13.800 --> 06:15.482
You can't ask a chatbot for wisdom.

06:15.942 --> 06:18.445
Wisdom requires human relationships.

06:19.026 --> 06:26.514
You only get wisdom by walking slowly with someone who has lived longer, seen more, and failed more than you have.

06:27.042 --> 06:30.668
A life that has learned to discern produces wisdom.

06:30.688 --> 06:33.894
And those are the lives we need to get close to if we want some for ourselves.

06:34.435 --> 06:35.997
You get wisdom by proximity.

06:36.338 --> 06:42.929
But the problem is we live in a culture that has incentivized us and manipulated us to avoid proximity.

06:43.350 --> 06:43.851
Think about it.

06:44.151 --> 06:47.156
We order food on screens to avoid talking to people.

06:49.040 --> 06:52.786
We text instead of calling to avoid the awkward silences.

06:53.250 --> 06:59.159
We curate our feeds to avoid people with whom we disagree, not even to not talk to them, but just to be exposed to what they think.

07:00.140 --> 07:06.489
We are designing relationship out of our lives as a culture, and in doing so, we are starving ourselves of wisdom.

07:07.511 --> 07:18.066
Now, this is why the Bible talks so much about honor, and over the course of this series, we've talked about honoring your parents, and I've mentioned I know how complicated that is for some of us, myself included.

07:18.210 --> 07:21.416
But the spiritual principle of honor is actually less about somebody else.

07:21.476 --> 07:23.559
It's more about what God's doing in me.

07:23.800 --> 07:25.823
It's less about just being polite.

07:25.864 --> 07:27.426
It's actually about access.

07:28.047 --> 07:36.322
When you honor the generation that came before you or when you honor your spiritual fathers and mothers, you are granting yourself access to their wisdom.

07:37.003 --> 07:40.850
You are admitting that you do not have it all figured out.

07:41.378 --> 07:44.622
This brings us to really the core message of today.

07:44.662 --> 07:50.750
We spent weeks talking about the fact that there is family kind of broadly or spouses.

07:50.771 --> 07:52.252
The last week we talked about parents.

07:52.573 --> 07:59.522
And each week, I've tried to highlight the fact that even if you aren't married, even if you don't have kids, this content really can help you.

07:59.803 --> 08:06.471
But if you wanted to, over the course of the last couple of weeks, if you didn't have kids and if you weren't married, you were kind of like, I guess I'm off the hook.

08:06.491 --> 08:08.434
Must be hard for all of you, right?

08:08.706 --> 08:11.249
But that's not what we're gonna experience this week.

08:11.309 --> 08:13.151
Nobody's getting a pass this week.

08:13.171 --> 08:18.497
You might not be a parent, you might not be married, but every single person listening to my voice is a child.

08:18.978 --> 08:19.738
You are a son.

08:20.459 --> 08:21.420
You are a daughter.

08:22.241 --> 08:25.445
And God has very specific instructions for his children.

08:26.186 --> 08:31.392
In Ephesians, the Apostle Paul points out something important from the 10 commandments written thousands of years ago.

08:31.412 --> 08:34.796
He says, children, obey your parents in the Lord, for this is right.

08:34.816 --> 08:36.978
He's quoting, and honor your father and mother,

08:37.122 --> 08:45.795
And then in parentheses, this is the first commandment with a promise that it may go well with you and that you may live long in the land.

08:45.855 --> 08:46.877
Isn't that interesting?

08:47.578 --> 08:52.706
Of all the 10 commandments, kind of the greatest hits that we often think about, even if you're not a person of faith, think about it.

08:52.726 --> 08:55.149
Do not murder, do not steal, do not commit adultery.

08:55.470 --> 09:02.120
This is the only commandment that comes with a built-in, specific incentive for adhering to it.

09:02.280 --> 09:06.226
Honor your father and mother that it may go well

09:06.914 --> 09:07.555
with you.

09:08.617 --> 09:18.716
God is saying that there is a unique spiritual weight, a connection to the favor of God in your life based on how we treat the generation that came before us.

09:19.738 --> 09:23.284
It acts as a predictor for the trajectory of our lives.

09:23.605 --> 09:30.578
But look, I know that the word of hope is one thing, but honor, that like feels way different.

09:31.042 --> 09:39.313
For some it's easy like honoring the generation before honoring your parents is easy I've heard from some of you like your parents They're incredible.

09:39.554 --> 09:40.655
They are worthy of honor.

09:40.675 --> 09:41.436
They're your heroes.

09:41.456 --> 09:44.220
That's amazing for others of us myself included.

09:44.260 --> 09:47.685
That's painful You're thinking feel you don't know my dad.

09:47.705 --> 09:51.931
You don't know my mom Does God really want me to honor dysfunction?

09:52.632 --> 09:57.138
So let's clear let's be clear on what honor is and what it isn't and

09:57.410 --> 10:01.516
Honor doesn't mean endorsing sin, it doesn't mean tolerating or obeying abuse.

10:01.996 --> 10:08.966
The Hebrew word that we translate honor is actually the word habbat, and it means to be heavy, weighty, or important.

10:09.626 --> 10:13.732
To honor someone is to give them weight in your life, substance.

10:13.772 --> 10:17.998
It means that you treat the relationship with them with significance uniquely.

10:18.619 --> 10:21.202
You don't treat them lightly or dismissively.

10:21.730 --> 10:29.258
And last week, we talked about impairancing that oftentimes what gets us in trouble in spaces of parenting is that we parent in the wrong time zone.

10:29.278 --> 10:32.761
That kids are at different ages and stages, but we don't always treat them like that.

10:33.161 --> 10:40.188
Well, it turns out actually there are different stages of how you honor your parents and the generation that came before you as well.

10:40.549 --> 10:41.850
And we're gonna look at those very quickly.

10:41.890 --> 10:46.355
The first stage is obedience as a child, specifically to your parents.

10:46.915 --> 10:49.778
If you're under 18 and you're living under your parents roof,

10:49.890 --> 10:51.652
Honor looks like obedience.

10:52.493 --> 11:00.682
It's a training ground for where you're going to honor the boundaries that they have set and be grateful for the provision that they have offered you.

11:01.202 --> 11:07.369
Now, I know how challenging this season can be, especially now in our moment.

11:07.929 --> 11:12.054
If you're a teenager, you probably feel like you are smarter than your parents at 12.

11:12.194 --> 11:13.375
I have a 16-year-old.

11:14.036 --> 11:15.858
He is for sure smarter than me.

11:16.290 --> 11:20.559
You've been helping your parents navigate culture, communication, technology.

11:21.040 --> 11:24.086
But here's the thing, do you don't have their wisdom yet?

11:24.747 --> 11:27.052
They're applied truthful knowledge.

11:27.092 --> 11:28.776
You don't have it, even if you think you do.

11:29.036 --> 11:32.203
And the more you think you have it, the less you do.

11:32.503 --> 11:33.906
And the more you need it.

11:34.626 --> 11:43.478
When you obey, even when you disagree, you are building a spiritual muscle to acknowledge that you don't know everything and that you remain teachable.

11:43.759 --> 11:47.544
You are reminding yourself that you are not the center of the universe.

11:47.584 --> 11:51.449
And if that's new information for you, I'm so sorry to be the one to break that to you.

11:52.951 --> 11:57.017
You need the same muscle, by the way, following God for the rest of your life.

11:58.038 --> 12:01.002
Stage two is respect as a young adult.

12:01.022 --> 12:03.666
When you leave the house, the dynamic changes.

12:04.034 --> 12:07.958
You no longer are under their authority, but you are still called to honor them.

12:08.578 --> 12:11.561
Honor evolves from obedience to respect.

12:11.601 --> 12:15.164
It means that you don't badmouthed your parents or assume their generosity.

12:15.225 --> 12:16.946
Young adults, let me say that again very quickly.

12:18.207 --> 12:27.876
What it means to respect your parents as a young adult is it means that you don't badmouthed them with your friends and you don't just assume or feel entitled to their, notice who it is, their money.

12:29.358 --> 12:31.920
It means that you proactively ask their counsel.

12:32.501 --> 12:33.842
You thank them for it.

12:34.178 --> 12:40.227
And even if you don't ultimately take their advice, you still acknowledge that they gave it to you with gratitude.

12:40.468 --> 12:43.372
You acknowledge the sacrifices that they made to get you there.

12:43.693 --> 12:50.643
Even if it's imperfect, I remember after we had our oldest child, I remember just after one night thinking to myself, my mom did this for me.

12:51.585 --> 12:53.708
And I called my mom, I was like, this is really hard.

12:53.748 --> 12:55.150
Thanks for doing this for me.

12:55.231 --> 12:56.052
I didn't even know.

12:56.092 --> 12:59.377
In the first century, as a matter of fact, they had a saying.

12:59.417 --> 13:02.642
They would say, the construction of the young is destruction.

13:02.882 --> 13:06.468
You don't even know what that phrase means and you already agree with it, right?

13:06.488 --> 13:16.744
Meaning that if you try to build your life for a society without the blueprint and the wisdom of the generation before you, you aren't building, you're just making a very expensive pile of rubble.

13:17.004 --> 13:28.041
We have the bricks, we have the information like we've never had before, but the generation before us will always carry the blueprint of wisdom that helps us stack them in the right direction.

13:28.863 --> 13:31.026
See, this ultimately leads

13:31.298 --> 13:34.622
to the third stage, which is compassion as an adult.

13:34.642 --> 13:42.353
A few years ago, I very clearly stepped into the sandwich generation, where I was caring for young kids at home and caring for aging parents.

13:42.433 --> 13:45.537
I was traveling to care for my mom every few weeks.

13:45.877 --> 13:51.265
I was taking care of most of her health care and financial decisions day to day, even at a distance.

13:51.285 --> 13:56.211
It was tiring, and honestly, it put a lot of pressure on our family and our church.

13:56.752 --> 14:01.298
But there was a big difference between pitying my mom in that final season of her life.

14:01.538 --> 14:02.859
and demonstrating compassion.

14:03.720 --> 14:05.302
Pitying creates distance.

14:05.322 --> 14:09.026
It looks at the decline of someone and says, man, that's sad, but it's not my problem.

14:09.506 --> 14:12.990
What's the minimum that I can do to get away with it and be viewed as caring?

14:13.651 --> 14:17.635
Pity assumes that because someone becomes outdated, they must become irrelevant.

14:18.896 --> 14:25.984
But see, too often in our fast-paced culture, when someone loses their utility, they lose their community too.

14:26.665 --> 14:27.986
It's not the way it's supposed to work.

14:28.770 --> 14:31.995
Compassion gets closer in moments and seasons like that.

14:32.676 --> 14:37.043
It remembers that the hands that are shaking now were once the hands that held you when you were helpless.

14:37.785 --> 14:46.098
They were the hands you reached out for when you weren't sure to go, where to go, the hands that you held them for comfort, those same ones are the ones you see shaking now.

14:46.914 --> 14:52.623
Compassion remembers that the voice that's quiet now is the same one that taught you to speak in the first place.

14:52.884 --> 14:56.029
The same voice you could pick out of a crowd and return to for safety.

14:56.329 --> 14:58.893
Compassion, it doesn't just see the struggle of today.

14:59.454 --> 15:01.758
It sees the love of each day along the way.

15:01.818 --> 15:03.461
And it remembers that that's who the person is.

15:04.322 --> 15:07.327
This is at the heart of the book of Proverbs in the Hebrew Scriptures.

15:07.407 --> 15:09.190
It focuses on wisdom.

15:09.731 --> 15:14.098
And wisdom has always fought against cultural instincts to discard what is old.

15:14.434 --> 15:21.183
One proverb reads this way, it says, listen to your father who gave you life and do not despise your mother when she is old.

15:22.165 --> 15:28.874
The idea is that they are worthy of respect and more than that, care, real care and compassion.

15:29.855 --> 15:38.307
Now we read a verse like that and the idea of despised, you know, I don't hate my parents, that's kind of strong, but in the Bible to despise, it didn't mean to hate.

15:38.828 --> 15:40.530
It means to treat lightly.

15:40.802 --> 15:42.524
It's the opposite of honor.

15:42.564 --> 15:53.779
If honor is heavy and weighted, to despise your mother or father when they get old is to treat them as weightless, to treat them as irrelevant, which is oftentimes the greatest fear of the generation before us.

15:54.359 --> 15:58.324
It's to treat her as a burden to be managed rather than a treasure to be cherished.

15:58.344 --> 16:03.912
It's to assume that because she has lost her usefulness, she has lost her significance.

16:03.932 --> 16:08.978
But the good news of Jesus, the gospel, calls us to see people the way that God sees them.

16:09.762 --> 16:12.286
God does not value us for our utility.

16:13.127 --> 16:15.291
He does not love us for our efficiency.

16:16.072 --> 16:25.788
And when we offer compassion to the generation before us, we are reminding the world that human worth is not a fluctuating stock price.

16:26.629 --> 16:28.993
It's the image of God in which you have been made.

16:29.995 --> 16:31.377
So have boundaries, get help.

16:31.417 --> 16:32.619
Don't try to do this alone.

16:32.659 --> 16:36.786
Don't treat your parents like, oh man, I'm just this,

16:36.866 --> 16:41.012
unlimited can do everything all the time person, but also don't treat your parents like garbage.

16:41.072 --> 16:42.894
You throw away when you're done using them.

16:44.717 --> 16:46.299
And look, I know that this is heavy.

16:47.321 --> 16:55.512
I know that for some of you, the idea of honoring or showing compassion, it feels impossible because of how deep the wounds that you carry are.

16:55.772 --> 16:57.815
And you might be thinking, Phil, you don't understand.

16:57.855 --> 16:59.337
My parents, they never honored me.

16:59.618 --> 17:00.799
They didn't protect me.

17:01.140 --> 17:05.586
And now you want me to see them as a treasure to treat them with honor?

17:06.658 --> 17:08.941
And this is where the rubber meets the road, I get it.

17:09.001 --> 17:13.928
But if you'll go back and you'll look at that commandment, it doesn't say to honor them because they're worthy of honor.

17:15.611 --> 17:18.936
Often times, I hope they are, but you honor them because of God.

17:19.757 --> 17:23.803
You honor them because you're trusting God with the principle that he's placed in life.

17:23.903 --> 17:25.826
And we do this with everybody.

17:25.886 --> 17:31.995
We might be able to be an interaction with, show honor and dignity to connect with and learn from.

17:32.916 --> 17:34.418
See, if we try to only

17:34.530 --> 17:39.015
honor the people that are worth it, will miss out on a whole bunch of what God has for us.

17:39.776 --> 17:50.347
On the flip side, if you try to honor people that you think don't deserve it or you try to honor people that feel really difficult and you do it out of your own strength because it's the right thing to do, you're going to burn out.

17:50.367 --> 17:51.128
We have a term for it.

17:51.148 --> 17:52.549
It's called compassion fatigue.

17:53.070 --> 17:55.072
We will run out of compassion.

17:55.592 --> 17:58.956
And so we need a power source greater than our own willpower.

17:59.557 --> 18:00.818
We need a model.

18:01.538 --> 18:12.870
And we've spent weeks in this series over and over again saying the same line, there are no perfect families, there are no perfect marriages, there are no perfect parents, but actually there is one perfect kid.

18:14.311 --> 18:15.212
Have you ever thought about that?

18:16.373 --> 18:25.202
Jesus, before his public ministry, for the first three decades of his life, we think of him as a savior, as a king, as a healer, but for the first three decades of his life, he was a son.

18:26.283 --> 18:29.106
Not just to his eternal heavenly father,

18:29.282 --> 18:30.805
but to his earthly parents.

18:30.825 --> 18:31.806
He had a mom, Mary.

18:31.847 --> 18:33.189
He had a dad, Joseph.

18:34.050 --> 18:47.294
And even though he was God in the flesh, even though he created the very galaxies that his parents would look up and see at night, scripture tells us in Luke two that he was submissive to his earthly parents.

18:47.354 --> 18:48.215
Can you imagine?

18:48.496 --> 18:49.918
He honored them.

18:49.958 --> 18:52.082
He listened to them.

18:52.642 --> 18:56.127
Some of you, you're like, well, I don't listen to my parents, because I'm smarter than them.

18:56.147 --> 18:57.249
I'm more capable than them.

18:57.549 --> 19:00.674
Can you imagine if that logic was the one Jesus followed?

19:02.717 --> 19:13.934
As a matter of fact, he, even on the cross, in his moment of greatest agony, he looked down, saw his mother, and made sure that she would be cared for by looking to John.

19:14.675 --> 19:17.940
He honored her to his very last breath.

19:19.041 --> 19:22.226
Jesus modeled the ultimate posture of a child, trust.

19:23.106 --> 19:28.354
He trusted his earthly parents with his childhood, and he trusted his heavenly father with his life and his death.

19:29.396 --> 19:47.924
In the Garden of Gethsemane on the night that he would be betrayed, the darkest night of his soul that he'd ever experienced in life, he didn't run, he didn't hide, he prayed, and he said to his father, Abba Father, Dad, if there's another way, if there's an option for us to redeem humans other than this one, can we do that one?

19:48.726 --> 19:51.570
But then he finishes, but not my will.

19:52.802 --> 19:54.224
yours, be done.

19:54.784 --> 20:01.171
And because he did that, because he was the perfect kid, he made a way for you and me to be adopted into the family.

20:02.132 --> 20:05.076
Which brings us to the reality that really we are all kids.

20:06.117 --> 20:10.562
We're kids in God's house, whether you've accepted the offer of adoption or not.

20:11.503 --> 20:21.554
But as I look around, honestly, as I think about my own heart, I see us trying to live out that identity in three very different ways as it connects and relates to God.

20:21.986 --> 20:25.270
The first kind of kid that I think we can slip into is the Venmo kid.

20:25.791 --> 20:28.854
Now it's important, like don't nudge your kids during this period of time.

20:28.874 --> 20:30.376
This is about all of us, okay?

20:30.396 --> 20:33.900
The Venmo kid has a transactional relationship with the father.

20:33.920 --> 20:41.149
They want the blessing, they want relief, they want provision, they want the perks, but they don't really want the father.

20:41.930 --> 20:45.234
We see this perfectly in the disciples, James and John.

20:45.570 --> 20:54.321
They pulled Jesus to the side in Mark 10, and they're trying to kind of negotiate the ultimate upgrade to the kingdom seeding chart.

20:54.401 --> 20:57.465
So they get Jesus, and if you can believe it, this is actually in the Bible.

20:57.485 --> 21:02.411
They say, teacher, we want you to do for us whatever we ask of you.

21:02.431 --> 21:06.936
And I'm sure Jesus is like, I think you misunderstand how this relationship works, right?

21:07.737 --> 21:09.639
They're not asking for how to better serve.

21:09.659 --> 21:11.762
They're actually asking how to better be served.

21:11.970 --> 21:14.153
They're asking for the corner office in the kingdom.

21:14.173 --> 21:21.422
They want one of them to sit on the right and one of them to sit on the left in these unique positions of influence and power in the kingdom of heaven.

21:21.963 --> 21:23.805
This is the Venmo mindset.

21:24.626 --> 21:26.588
It treats prayer like an invoice.

21:27.069 --> 21:29.832
It says, God, I let my nets down for you.

21:29.933 --> 21:31.234
I followed you.

21:31.254 --> 21:33.197
I sent the payment.

21:33.257 --> 21:34.258
Now, where is my product?

21:35.520 --> 21:37.522
The Venmo kid works for God's stuff.

21:38.210 --> 21:43.257
And if we're honest, we've all been there with our earthly parents probably and definitely with God.

21:44.238 --> 21:47.342
The second type of kid is the report card kid.

21:47.362 --> 21:51.388
This is the one that connects back to the toddler playing hide and seek.

21:51.408 --> 21:55.513
The report card kid is obsessed with their spiritual report card.

21:55.934 --> 21:59.178
They are constantly checking to see if they're making the right grade.

21:59.198 --> 22:00.680
Did I volunteer enough?

22:01.461 --> 22:02.663
Did I read my Bible enough?

22:02.903 --> 22:04.645
Did I avoid enough sin?

22:05.547 --> 22:08.050
The report card kid works for status.

22:08.290 --> 22:15.319
They're terrified that if they get a C minus in morality, that God will revoke their acceptance letter to heaven.

22:16.180 --> 22:16.781
So what do they do?

22:17.902 --> 22:18.322
They hide.

22:18.363 --> 22:22.888
They cover their eyes like the ostrich.

22:22.928 --> 22:25.231
They hide the bad grades of their life.

22:25.251 --> 22:29.036
They only show God the stuff that they feel like will impress them.

22:29.977 --> 22:33.621
Now, they're exhausted because they're always performing.

22:34.242 --> 22:37.266
They think that they're a candidate for a job, not a child in a home.

22:38.370 --> 22:53.566
And this is a type of kid that when people like this show up this way to God, I'm a little scared for them because of the way they think about report card sounds very familiar to the way that Jesus talks about a future moment of judgment that he describes this way.

22:54.027 --> 23:04.338
It says, on that day, many will say to me, Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name and cast demons in your name and do so many mighty works

23:04.546 --> 23:08.973
in your name, and then I, Jesus, declare to them, I never knew you.

23:09.033 --> 23:14.923
Depart from me, you workers of lawlessness.

23:16.306 --> 23:16.887
And look, I get it.

23:16.907 --> 23:24.018
I know that for many of us, if we were honest today, we would probably identify with some version of a report card kid right now.

23:24.940 --> 23:26.162
And I just want to name

23:26.274 --> 23:29.399
the really exhausting way of living this way.

23:29.419 --> 23:34.667
See, the big problem with a report card living is that a report card is only valid for a semester.

23:36.710 --> 23:38.373
You can get straight A's for a season.

23:38.934 --> 23:41.418
You can white knuckle your way with God for a season.

23:41.698 --> 23:44.322
You can do every good deed and read your Bible every day.

23:44.603 --> 23:47.948
You can feel so good and feel so safe as long as you're doing that.

23:48.990 --> 23:51.634
But then the semester ends, the season changes and you slip.

23:52.258 --> 23:53.099
You lose your temper.

23:53.139 --> 24:05.734
You click on that website again and suddenly the report card drops to a D. And because your identity is tied to the grave, the entire sense of self and identity that you had, that you constructed by your own behavior, collapses.

24:05.774 --> 24:13.824
And you will spend your whole life on that treadmill running just to stay in the same place.

24:13.844 --> 24:16.327
Terrified that if you stop running, God will stop loving you.

24:17.548 --> 24:18.930
It's a miserable way to live.

24:19.394 --> 24:21.456
It's a form of spiritual slavery.

24:21.476 --> 24:23.598
And Jesus, he didn't die to make you a slave.

24:23.898 --> 24:25.179
He died to make you a son.

24:25.940 --> 24:27.381
He died to make you a daughter.

24:27.401 --> 24:28.883
He died to make you his child.

24:30.064 --> 24:33.107
So you have the Venmo kid, you have the report card kid.

24:33.187 --> 24:34.989
Jesus, he offers us a third way.

24:35.289 --> 24:36.710
And that is the fridge art kid.

24:37.111 --> 24:37.611
Bear with me.

24:38.492 --> 24:40.634
If you have little kids, you kind of already know where I'm going.

24:41.234 --> 24:43.997
Think about the art that's on your refrigerator at home.

24:44.037 --> 24:47.040
If you have little kids, it's probably not professional.

24:47.680 --> 24:49.362
It might be kind of messy.

24:49.442 --> 24:52.825
It's usually drawn with a dull crayon or a fading marker.

24:52.865 --> 24:54.467
Maybe it's on construction paper.

24:54.527 --> 24:59.291
If the report card kids saw it, they would hide it because it isn't perfect.

25:00.773 --> 25:07.239
But the fridge art kid, he runs into the kitchen and he holds it up and says, look dad, I made this for you.

25:08.200 --> 25:12.444
And the father doesn't like get down and look at it and go, well, let's talk about your shading technique.

25:14.866 --> 25:19.090
He grabs a magnet and he puts it in the highest place of honor

25:19.618 --> 25:20.059
in the house.

25:21.360 --> 25:21.621
Why?

25:21.661 --> 25:32.215
Because the Venmo kid works for the wallet, the report card kid works for the status, but the fridge art kid, the fridge art kid can walk in security, can walk in safety.

25:32.235 --> 25:34.618
They aren't trying to earn the father's love.

25:34.658 --> 25:37.182
They know they already have it.

25:37.202 --> 25:44.732
They create, they serve, they live their lives as a response to the love that they are increasingly aware of and that will never change.

25:46.094 --> 25:49.458
The good news of Jesus, the gospel, it's foolishness to the Venmo kid.

25:49.666 --> 25:51.228
because they can't buy it.

25:51.248 --> 25:54.271
It's foolishness to the report card kid because they can't earn it.

25:55.373 --> 25:58.977
But to the fridge art kid, it's the power of God.

25:59.878 --> 26:07.827
Because healthy children receive their identity as a gift, not a great one they can't earn even if they tried.

26:09.129 --> 26:10.270
And listen, I needed you to hear this.

26:10.791 --> 26:16.978
Being a fridge art kid, it doesn't mean that you are perfect or that your drawing is always the prettiest, you know that.

26:17.314 --> 26:20.938
My daughter Maisie, who's turning 14 today, happy birthday to Maisie.

26:21.418 --> 26:38.695
Eight years ago, she was doing an art project with a friend, their same age, and she looked at her friend's project, which actually was really nice for the age that they were, and then she looked at her own, and it was kind of messy, and she looked up at me and said, Daddy, why does hers look so much better than mine, you know?

26:39.976 --> 26:44.360
But the truth is, as great as her friend's art was, it was never up on our fridge.

26:45.541 --> 26:46.162
Maisie's was.

26:47.330 --> 26:50.013
Her friend's a great kid, but she's not my daughter.

26:51.654 --> 26:53.436
That's the difference.

26:53.456 --> 26:56.839
The fridge is not a fancy gallery for the talented.

26:56.979 --> 27:00.282
It's a family gallery for the beloved.

27:02.465 --> 27:05.648
But for some of you, it's even heavier than that.

27:06.989 --> 27:11.814
Some of you, you're not holding messy art in front of God, you're holding broken pieces.

27:13.155 --> 27:16.498
I remember a moment with one of my own kids years ago,

27:16.610 --> 27:19.594
done something that they knew they weren't supposed to do.

27:20.095 --> 27:22.077
They'd broken something valuable in the house.

27:22.097 --> 27:27.304
They knew they weren't supposed to do it because we had repeatedly told them, please don't do that because you're going to break that thing.

27:27.905 --> 27:30.128
And then they did the thing and then they broke the thing, right?

27:30.989 --> 27:34.053
Now the human instinct in that moment is to hide as a kid.

27:34.213 --> 27:36.576
And as a kid from a violent home, that's what I would have done.

27:36.596 --> 27:37.598
That's what I did do.

27:38.519 --> 27:39.240
But I'll never forget.

27:40.361 --> 27:42.124
When this happened, my child didn't run away from me.

27:43.265 --> 27:43.986
They ran to me.

27:45.026 --> 27:51.135
They came into the room, tears were streaming down their face, and they just buried their face into my chest.

27:52.757 --> 27:53.738
They didn't have a fix.

27:55.160 --> 27:56.342
They didn't have an excuse.

27:57.604 --> 27:58.786
They just had a broken mess.

28:00.107 --> 28:00.829
And do you know what I did?

28:00.869 --> 28:04.053
Well, I didn't check their report card.

28:05.816 --> 28:08.419
I didn't send them a Venmo request for the damages.

28:10.142 --> 28:13.106
I wrapped my arms around them, and I held them.

28:14.402 --> 28:17.226
Because in that moment, I didn't care about what was broken.

28:17.246 --> 28:19.730
I cared that my child felt broken.

28:21.833 --> 28:24.116
That's the gospel.

28:24.136 --> 28:26.940
Some of you, you're sitting here today holding the broken pieces of your life.

28:28.142 --> 28:30.004
You have broken relationships with your parents.

28:30.024 --> 28:32.528
You have broken pieces of your own integrity.

28:32.808 --> 28:39.538
You are exhausted from trying to hide all of it, just like the report card kit.

28:40.546 --> 28:43.490
You're exhausted from trying to pay for them like the Venmo kid.

28:43.510 --> 28:46.213
And the father is saying, stop running away.

28:46.694 --> 28:47.895
Stop hiding.

28:48.136 --> 28:50.639
Just bring the pieces to me.

28:52.020 --> 28:54.163
We're about to sing a song together you may be familiar with.

28:54.223 --> 28:55.445
It's called Run to the Father.

28:56.626 --> 28:58.829
And the lyrics of the song say, I run to the father.

28:59.990 --> 29:01.072
I fall into grace.

29:02.734 --> 29:03.955
I'm done with the hiding.

29:05.638 --> 29:07.860
I'm done with the shame.

29:07.880 --> 29:09.202
And that is your invitation today.

29:10.498 --> 29:11.540
You don't have to be perfect.

29:11.560 --> 29:12.541
You just have to be present.

29:12.561 --> 29:13.182
Just show up.

29:13.242 --> 29:15.305
Bring the mess.

29:15.325 --> 29:16.667
You don't have to fix the drawing.

29:17.449 --> 29:18.450
Just bring it into the kitchen.

29:19.632 --> 29:25.601
Because healthy children, they receive their identity as a gift from a loving father, not as a great.

29:27.083 --> 29:29.447
For some of you, you've been following Jesus a long time.

29:30.629 --> 29:35.356
And this is an important and helpful reminder at the end of a series that hopefully God's gonna do something within your life.

29:35.897 --> 29:36.818
Maybe he already is.

29:37.666 --> 29:40.370
For some of you, you've never made a decision to follow Jesus.

29:40.390 --> 29:44.936
You know that if that's the kind of love that's available, you don't have a category for that.

29:44.956 --> 29:47.940
It's not what you experience, but if that's what's available, you want it.

29:49.102 --> 29:58.055
So I just say, even as we sing this song, even over these next few minutes, for you to just pray a simple prayer in your heart to God that acknowledges God, I can't get back to you on my own.

29:59.597 --> 30:02.040
I want to accept the gift that Jesus has made available to me.

30:02.120 --> 30:06.226
I'm in whatever that means, whatever that looks like.

30:06.914 --> 30:09.397
because this really is the love that's available.

30:09.657 --> 30:14.603
We are all God's children in that we are created in His image with infinite dignity, value, and worth.

30:14.863 --> 30:17.827
But to be in His family, you've got to be adopted.

30:20.129 --> 30:21.971
The invitation papers are in front of you.

30:22.992 --> 30:24.014
The payment has been made.

30:24.054 --> 30:28.499
And He's just waiting for you to run to Him.

30:30.441 --> 30:31.282
Would you pray with me?

30:33.634 --> 30:47.938
God, for each and every one of us today, we have our own story of what it's meant to be a child, to grow up in the kind of home that we've grown up in, to have the parent figures that we had, to have the relatives around us and the community that surrounds us.

30:49.141 --> 30:55.692
And right now, God, I pray that for those that those things are helpful connectors that you would use them to connect to the kind of love that you have for us.

30:55.732 --> 30:59.378
And for those of us, God, that those were really painful and really difficult.

30:59.714 --> 31:04.820
Honestly, I remember thinking to myself, I learned about you, I got one dad, I don't want, I'm not sure I need a second one.

31:04.860 --> 31:14.131
And so father, I pray that your love, your love that's greater than any earthly love would be what we feel now.

31:15.172 --> 31:22.421
And that this call to run to you would be one that we embrace to the deepest parts of who we are.

31:22.441 --> 31:27.026
For those of us that are doing it for the first time in a long time, we've been away, meet us there.

31:27.842 --> 31:37.389
And for those who have never done it, God, would you just give them that simple prayer in their heart to come to you right now in Jesus' name?

31:38.593 --> 31:38.994
Amen.

